event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0b9e2fae7aadca590169e3dd2258a481938fb13500cf3e1ffc","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":974,"text":"Below is a step-by-step way to implement **memoized (top-down) Fibonacci** in Python, with design choices explained as we go.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Decide the function behavior (API + input validation)\n\nWe’ll implement:\n\n- `fib(n)` returns the nth Fibonacci number\n- Require `n` to be a non-negative integer\n\n```python\ndef fib(n: int) -> int:\n    if not isinstance(n, int):\n        raise TypeError(\"n must be an integer\")\n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"n must be non-negative\")\n```\n\n**Why this design?**\n- A clear function signature (`fib(n: int) -> int`) makes intent explicit.\n- Validating inputs avoids surprising behavior when the recursion would otherwise run with bad values.\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Choose the memo storage structure\n\nMemoization means: “cache results of subproblems so we don’t recompute them.”\n\nUse a dictionary:\n\n- keys: `k`\n- values: `F(k)`\n\n```python\n    memo = {}\n```\n\n**Why `dict`?**\n- Fibonacci indices are integers, and a dict is a straightforward mapping.\n- It’s flexible (doesn’t require you to pre-allocate an array up front).\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Use a nested recursive helper\n\nWe’ll write a helper that does the recursion and uses the memo.\n\n```python\n    def helper(k: int) -> int:\n```\n\n**Why a nested helper?**\n- The `memo` dictionary is shared across all recursive calls.\n- Keeping `memo` inside `fib` avoids accidental reuse across separate calls to `fib(n)`.\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Implement base cases\n\nFibonacci base cases:\n\n- `F(0) = 0`\n- `F(1) = 1`\n\n```python\n        if k == 0:\n            return 0\n        if k == 1:\n            return 1\n```\n\n**Why early returns?**\n- Base cases stop recursion and define the simplest known answers.\n\n---\n\n## Step 5: Add the memoization check\n\nBefore doing any work, see if we’ve already computed `F(k)`.\n\n```python\n        if k in memo:\n            return memo[k]\n```\n\n**Why this check comes early?**\n- It prevents recomputing overlapping subproblems.\n- In Fibonacci, many calls repeatedly ask for the same `F(k)`.\n\n---\n\n## Step 6: Recursively compute and store\n\nIf not cached, compute:\n\n- `F(k) = F(k-1) + F(k-2)`\n\nThen store:\n\n```python\n        memo[k] = helper(k - 1) + helper(k - 2)\n        return memo[k]\n```\n\n**Why store after computing?**\n- We compute the value first (so we’re correct),\n- then cache it so any future request for `F(k)` is O(1).\n\n---\n\n## Step 7: Return the final result\n\n```python\n    return helper(n)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Complete working implementation\n\n```python\ndef fib(n: int) -> int:\n    if not isinstance(n, int):\n        raise TypeError(\"n must be an integer\")\n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"n must be non-negative\")\n\n    memo = {}\n\n    def helper(k: int) -> int:\n        if k == 0:\n            return 0\n        if k == 1:\n            return 1\n\n        if k in memo:\n            return memo[k]\n\n        memo[k] = helper(k - 1) + helper(k - 2)\n        return memo[k]\n\n    return helper(n)\n```\n\nExample usage:\n```python\nprint(fib(6))  # 8\nprint(fib(10)) # 55\n```\n\n---\n\n## Note on recursion depth (practical design consideration)\nThis approach uses recursion, so for large `n` (roughly > 900–1000), Python may hit the recursion limit. For very large `n`, an iterative DP version avoids that.\n\n---\n\n## (Optional) Alternative: Python’s built-in memoization\nPython can do memoization automatically via `functools.lru_cache`:\n\n```python\nfrom functools import lru_cache\n\n@lru_cache(maxsize=None)\ndef fib(n: int) -> int:\n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError(\"n must be non-negative\")\n    if n < 2:\n        return n\n    return fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2)\n```\n\nThis is functionally the same idea, but you avoid manually managing the `memo` dict.\n\n"}

